62
00:05:12,453 --> 00:05:19,374
And that's natural when you're dealing with a long-running franchise, but we were really encountering this for the first time.

63
00:05:19,374 --> 00:05:27,556
As a result of the ups and downs of that long history, you have sort of mixed feelings and loyalty around sort of a fan base.

64
00:05:27,556 --> 00:05:32,977
We had new contenders at that time in 2008, 2009 when we were starting this in the likes of...

65
00:05:33,437 --> 00:05:37,579
Assassin's Creed or Uncharted or God of War 3, there was a new generation of hardware

66
00:05:37,579 --> 00:05:42,922
and there were new contenders to the Action-Adventure crown that were bringing their new angles

67
00:05:42,922 --> 00:05:46,304
and really doing some great stuff around Action-Adventure too.

68
00:05:47,460 --> 00:05:53,044
Also we had a generational change, not only in hardware, but it was also in terms of our

69
00:05:53,044 --> 00:05:55,045
fan base and our audience as well.

70
00:05:55,045 --> 00:05:59,368
Obviously, 17 years later, the people that may have started playing Tomb Raider in 96

71
00:05:59,368 --> 00:06:01,610
may be different people today.

72
00:06:01,610 --> 00:06:03,131
They may have never played it before.

73
00:06:03,131 --> 00:06:05,092
Some people would have and some people won't.

74
00:06:05,092 --> 00:06:09,595
So we also had to think about how we spanned from one generation to another, and that was

75
00:06:09,595 --> 00:06:12,397
some of the challenges we were dealing with going into this project.

76
00:06:12,797 --> 00:06:18,760
So, these were some of the things we did coming off the back of a trilogy we created in Legend,

77
00:06:18,760 --> 00:06:20,061
Anniversary and Underworld.

78
00:06:20,061 --> 00:06:24,664
And as we finished that up, that was very much based on a formula very much from Core

79
00:06:24,664 --> 00:06:27,305
Design and we were successful with that formula.

80
00:06:27,305 --> 00:06:33,209
But going into this new phase of Tomb Raider, these were some of the challenges we felt

81
00:06:33,209 --> 00:06:34,669
like we had to deal with.

82
00:06:34,669 --> 00:06:35,890
From a goals perspective...

83
00:06:36,410 --> 00:06:41,332
Ultimately, we wanted people to fall in love with Tomb Raider once again, with this next game.

84
00:06:41,332 --> 00:06:43,952
And this is what we started with way back when.

85
00:06:43,952 --> 00:06:48,874
We had a real goal to make Lara somebody you could get to know again, to humanise her,

86
00:06:48,874 --> 00:06:53,975
for her to be less of this superhero that you knew because you played N number of games and seen the movies,

87
00:06:53,975 --> 00:07:00,057
but somebody that we actually got to know once again and fall in love with over again, like it happened in 1996.

88
00:07:01,183 --> 00:07:04,806
So therefore we had to challenge the expectations around Lara and the brand.

89
00:07:04,806 --> 00:07:09,931
We had to make sure that we were embracing this new audience that maybe hadn't played Tomb Raider before,

90
00:07:09,931 --> 00:07:14,116
or maybe they were old fans that were revisiting that we had lost along the way.

91
00:07:14,116 --> 00:07:17,038
And to do that we really felt like we had to make some big changes.

92
00:07:17,676 --> 00:07:24,162
Quality and innovation was synonymous with Tomb Raider in 1996 and along the way it was

93
00:07:24,162 --> 00:07:27,124
one of the pioneers in action adventure.

94
00:07:27,124 --> 00:07:31,728
So we wanted to put that stamp back into this game, we wanted to be right up there as the

95
00:07:31,728 --> 00:07:32,889
best of the best.

96
00:07:32,889 --> 00:07:36,873
So these were high goals that we had at the beginning of this project.

97
00:07:37,093 --> 00:07:42,497
And ultimately we still had to thread the needle because it's a tightrope to walk between old and new.

98
00:07:42,497 --> 00:07:48,601
That we had this franchise with this fanbase and all this rich history, but we wanted to take it to a new place.

99
00:07:48,601 --> 00:07:54,325
And that tightrope is a very, very narrow one to walk because too much old and it feels like it's...

100
00:07:54,565 --> 00:07:59,646
the old game, and it may as well be a sequel, too much new, and maybe it wouldn't be Tomb Raider anymore.

101
00:07:59,646 --> 00:08:08,529
And whilst we sort of approached this with a blank canvas, the actual reality was it was a very, very narrow razor that we had to walk.

102
00:08:08,529 --> 00:08:10,690
So it's tough doing these types of games as reboots.

103
00:08:12,231 --> 00:08:16,733
Originally, it actually didn't start as a reboot, it was almost a pseudo-sequel.

104
00:08:16,733 --> 00:08:23,015
And as ideas were being kicked around in the early stages of development in concept and in pre-production,

105
00:08:23,015 --> 00:08:27,196
it became clear that to achieve the goals we just set out in slides before,

106
00:08:27,196 --> 00:08:30,437
that we ultimately had to wipe the slate clean.

107
00:08:30,437 --> 00:08:36,480
And we needed to make a fresh start with this character, and a fresh start with no preconceptions built in for the audience.

108
00:08:36,760 --> 00:08:41,981
So ultimately it became an origin story and we were buoyed and encouraged by other franchises

109
00:08:41,981 --> 00:08:47,642
around us outside video games where we looked and we felt that they had actually taken a

110
00:08:47,642 --> 00:08:48,462
similar approach.

111
00:08:48,462 --> 00:08:54,164
So here we have Bond and Batman that are two amazing examples outside games where Bond

112
00:08:54,164 --> 00:08:59,425
has been around 50 years this year and has just done a billion dollars at the box office.

113
00:08:59,425 --> 00:09:05,827
So it's as fresh as it was 50 years ago today and Batman is in a similar place as well.

114
00:09:06,267 --> 00:09:12,210
And I think the key thing about this and why we looked here is because in games having 17 years of history,

115
00:09:12,210 --> 00:09:16,333
ultimately we were one of the first to have to go through this.

116
00:09:16,333 --> 00:09:21,856
You know, it's a shorter time scale in games in terms of people having franchises

117
00:09:21,856 --> 00:09:26,719
because game space is much narrower and obviously younger than things like movies.

118
00:09:27,119 --> 00:09:32,983
So we looked outside and what we felt was these franchises have done such a great job

119
00:09:32,983 --> 00:09:38,346
in retaining the DNA of their characters and their franchises but bringing it to new generations

120
00:09:38,346 --> 00:09:40,948
and really making it feel fresh.

121
00:09:40,948 --> 00:09:45,891
And they've managed to span generation to generation but retain their franchise integrity.

122
00:09:46,632 --> 00:09:52,660
So we were very much inspired by this and this origin story, but we really had to find our own slant on that.

123
00:09:52,660 --> 00:09:58,808
And ultimately, we knew we wanted to make an origin story, we knew that we had these high goals,

124
00:09:58,808 --> 00:10:04,054
but we were looking in early stages around how we could hang our hooks on something that made it feel fresh.

125
00:10:04,475 --> 00:10:06,998
for Tomb Raider and also fresh in the industry.

126
00:10:06,998 --> 00:10:12,964
So many ideas were thrown around and explored in the early stages of development

127
00:10:12,964 --> 00:10:18,169
and ultimately we landed in a spot where we found something we felt that we could hang our hooks on,

128
00:10:18,169 --> 00:10:20,091
which I'll hand over to Noah to discuss.

129
00:10:20,251 --> 00:10:27,795
Yeah, it was important to understand that in humanizing Lara by rolling her back to an origin story,

130
00:10:27,795 --> 00:10:32,637
we were making her closer to you or I and hopefully a more relatable character.

131
00:10:32,637 --> 00:10:36,059
But the most exciting part about it was that we could then take her on that journey,

132
00:10:36,059 --> 00:10:39,821
we could take the players on that journey to becoming the Tomb Raider.

133
00:10:39,821 --> 00:10:40,081
But...

134
00:10:40,862 --> 00:10:44,462
We needed a sense of identity beyond just origin story.

135
00:10:44,462 --> 00:10:47,023
So we looked at a lot of different things,

136
00:10:47,023 --> 00:10:50,264
but ultimately we came upon the idea of survival stories.

137
00:10:50,264 --> 00:10:52,164
And for us, we were really inspired

138
00:10:52,164 --> 00:10:56,625
by the real world tales of survival.

139
00:10:56,625 --> 00:11:00,026
We have Aaron Ralston here, who featured in 127 Hours,

140
00:11:00,026 --> 00:11:04,167
ultimately had to cut off his own arm in order to survive.

141
00:11:04,167 --> 00:11:05,907
Or the rugby players in the Andes

142
00:11:05,907 --> 00:11:10,028
who resorted to cannibalism in order to survive.

143
00:11:10,028 --> 00:11:10,388
These are.

144
00:11:11,089 --> 00:11:14,592
at the surface, very dark stories.

145
00:11:14,592 --> 00:11:16,834
But what was interesting to us is

146
00:11:16,834 --> 00:11:21,858
there was a sense of inspiration to these stories,

147
00:11:21,858 --> 00:11:24,220
that there was a memorable journey here

148
00:11:24,220 --> 00:11:29,025
that showcased the human capacity to overcome.

149
00:11:29,025 --> 00:11:30,746
And ultimately, through that journey,

150
00:11:30,746 --> 00:11:33,028
these people were changed as well.

151
00:11:33,028 --> 00:11:34,990
So that idea that we could.

152
00:11:35,530 --> 00:11:40,918
take Lara's origin story and tell it through the lens of survival was very compelling to

153
00:11:40,918 --> 00:11:44,323
us and we felt would help humanize her as a character.

154
00:11:44,323 --> 00:11:48,329
But we had to zoom in a little bit and understand what that meant.

155
00:11:48,329 --> 00:11:49,731
I think what we found was that

156
00:11:50,552 --> 00:11:53,455
Survival can be many different things to many different people.

157
00:11:53,455 --> 00:11:57,058
So we tried to clarify what it would mean to us in this game.

158
00:11:57,058 --> 00:11:59,040
So first of all, survival action.

159
00:11:59,040 --> 00:12:00,761
And that's to sort of balance out this sense

160
00:12:00,761 --> 00:12:04,364
that there's a simulation version of survival as well.

161
00:12:04,364 --> 00:12:07,307
But because pace was incredibly important to our game

162
00:12:07,307 --> 00:12:10,970
experience, we really wanted to capture that survival action.

163
00:12:10,970 --> 00:12:13,852
But it would still be brutal, perilous, raw.

164
00:12:13,852 --> 00:12:15,353
This would be the harsh environment

165
00:12:15,353 --> 00:12:17,315
that would forge Lara.

166
00:12:17,315 --> 00:12:18,836
And it would ultimately ask her.

167
00:12:19,377 --> 00:12:22,800
to fight to survive, that we wanted to showcase

168
00:12:22,800 --> 00:12:26,763
her determination as a character, her endurance, her will to live in the face

169
00:12:26,763 --> 00:12:27,664
of death,

170
00:12:27,664 --> 00:12:31,847
but also as a character who's sort of an intellectual hero.

171
00:12:31,847 --> 00:12:35,771
We love that aspect of resourcefulness that we saw in these stories. Here's

172
00:12:35,771 --> 00:12:36,591
people who

173
00:12:36,591 --> 00:12:40,054
had nothing and they had to make do with what they had and it was really

174
00:12:40,054 --> 00:12:43,077
that ability to adapt to their situation

175
00:12:43,077 --> 00:12:46,500
that let them survive. So these are all things that very much resonated with

176
00:12:47,020 --> 00:12:51,366
the franchise for us. So just to capture some in a sentence, the idea of the

177
00:12:51,366 --> 00:12:55,191
determination to go beyond human endurance, taking the moment of raw

178
00:12:55,191 --> 00:12:59,917
instinct and stretching it. It's about overcoming that near-death experiences

179
00:12:59,917 --> 00:13:00,919
time and time again.

180
00:13:01,900 --> 00:13:05,721
So we had now an inspiration in survival.

181
00:13:05,721 --> 00:13:08,302
And at the end of this concept phase,

182
00:13:08,302 --> 00:13:11,403
we sort of summed that up with a survivor is born.

183
00:13:11,403 --> 00:13:14,083
And ultimately, that became our tagline.

184
00:13:14,083 --> 00:13:16,344
But internally, it was also a guiding vision.

185
00:13:16,344 --> 00:13:19,985
It captured that idea of Lara's origin story seen

186
00:13:19,985 --> 00:13:21,405
through the lens of survival.

187
00:13:21,405 --> 00:13:24,526
So with that, we felt we had a very clear sense

188
00:13:24,526 --> 00:13:26,367
of a high-level vision for the game.

189
00:13:26,367 --> 00:13:27,987
So I'll turn it over to Daryl to get back

190
00:13:27,987 --> 00:13:28,908
into production a little bit.

191
00:13:28,908 --> 00:13:29,408
Thanks, Noah.

192
00:13:33,095 --> 00:13:39,463
So now we had our identity, at least a hook we felt we could work with, and a high level of what we wanted to do with the game.

193
00:13:39,463 --> 00:13:47,532
And ultimately going into the high level in production, I guess I wanted to sort of carve out what we use, which is a rule of thirds.

194
00:13:47,532 --> 00:13:51,076
This at a high level is what we've done on the last couple of projects at Crystal.

195
00:13:51,256 --> 00:13:53,458
including Lara Croft and the Guardian of Light.

196
00:13:53,458 --> 00:13:56,340
And essentially it's just breaking your production from a high level into

197
00:13:56,340 --> 00:14:00,123
one third for pre-production and what we call vertical slice,

198
00:14:00,123 --> 00:14:02,125
which is the end of pre-production for us,

199
00:14:02,125 --> 00:14:05,127
one third for production, and one third for post-production.

200
00:14:05,809 --> 00:14:11,031
Some commentary around that, I mean typically what we've seen, you know we've all made a lot of games here,

201
00:14:11,031 --> 00:14:17,214
is that that first third and that last third tend to get squished and shortchanged in lots of ways.

202
00:14:17,214 --> 00:14:23,398
And we felt that it was important that we actually maintained sort of an uncompromising view on what we wanted in each third,

203
00:14:23,398 --> 00:14:27,640
and therefore shape the production around this rule of thirds.

204
00:14:27,640 --> 00:14:32,002
We wanted to give as much time as we could in post-production to polish and refine.

205
00:14:32,482 --> 00:14:36,824
what we had and we wanted to make sure that every step of the way in pre-production and

206
00:14:36,824 --> 00:14:39,605
vertical slice it was clear what game we were making.

207
00:14:39,605 --> 00:14:44,768
So there's always a lot of pressures in each one of these phases and even though it was

208
00:14:44,768 --> 00:14:49,070
a four year period essentially once we found our hook of survival in early exploration

209
00:14:49,070 --> 00:14:54,412
really that pre-production to vertical slice phase was one year, production was one year

210
00:14:54,412 --> 00:14:58,634
and post-production was one year and we're going to walk through each one of those phases

211
00:14:58,634 --> 00:15:01,755
at a high level and show some videos of where we were at each stage.

212
00:15:03,407 --> 00:15:10,731
So some quick stats around it. We made a 12 hour plus experience. 10 to 12 hours is what we were aiming for.

213
00:15:10,731 --> 00:15:16,734
We actually found that once people played the game, we saw them play for 14, 18, 20, 25 and more.

214
00:15:16,734 --> 00:15:20,896
So we've been very pleased with the feedback.

215
00:15:22,634 --> 00:15:28,676
absolutely built a very, very big production in this game because it was a complex, big game to make.

216
00:15:28,676 --> 00:15:31,197
So we had to focus very much on our tools and pipeline.

