00:15:44,482 --> 00:15:46,703
an army of hundreds making this game,

221
00:15:46,703 --> 00:15:49,646
we were gonna be under a hundred ultimately

222
00:15:49,646 --> 00:15:52,888
making this game happen on the single player side.

223
00:15:52,888 --> 00:15:54,990
So we wanted tools and pipelines

224
00:15:54,990 --> 00:15:56,891
to really be that driving force

225
00:15:56,891 --> 00:15:58,673
to help us iterate quickly,

226
00:15:58,673 --> 00:16:00,154
to help designers and artists

227
00:16:00,154 --> 00:16:02,055
really have the power in their hands.

228
00:16:02,055 --> 00:16:04,577
So it was a big investment in the tools that we made

229
00:16:04,577 --> 00:16:06,859
to make a level editor that really put the power in

230
00:16:06,859 --> 00:16:09,121
the content creator's hands with live editing,

231
00:16:09,121 --> 00:16:11,182
live updating, and a very flexible,

232
00:16:11,182 --> 00:16:12,944
powerful system to create content.

233
00:16:13,644 --> 00:16:16,908
We totally turned our production methodology on its head.

234
00:16:16,908 --> 00:16:20,332
In many ways in this production, we did things very, very differently.

235
00:16:20,332 --> 00:16:23,755
And because we were building such an important origin story,

236
00:16:23,755 --> 00:16:26,779
we actually made a beat-driven development process.

237
00:16:26,779 --> 00:16:29,281
Now we'll actually go into a little bit more detail there.

238
00:16:29,281 --> 00:16:34,107
But essentially, in previous games, it was saying we wanted to do 10 or 12 hours.

239
00:16:34,687 --> 00:16:39,328
What's the footprint for that? It's about this big, let's fill it with stuff.

240
00:16:39,328 --> 00:16:47,830
And this one, it was, we still wanted 10 to 12 hours, but we wanted every moment to feel like it fitted into a larger picture.

241
00:16:47,830 --> 00:16:54,492
So the scheduling and production was built around beats and moments that we wanted to deliver from an experiential standpoint.

242
00:16:54,492 --> 00:17:01,793
And that's how we costed things, that's how we produced things, and that's how we scheduled out the whole production.

243
00:17:01,793 --> 00:17:04,494
So the actual footprint from the game was built from beats.

244
00:17:04,574 --> 00:17:07,497
which we'll go into again a little later with Noah.

245
00:17:07,497 --> 00:17:10,159
We also had a very modular level design process,

246
00:17:10,159 --> 00:17:11,961
especially on the art side,

247
00:17:11,961 --> 00:17:14,102
that ultimately we had to build big worlds,

248
00:17:14,102 --> 00:17:16,425
biggest worlds we've ever built for Tomb Raider,

249
00:17:16,425 --> 00:17:19,787
and we had to do it in a way where we kept the fidelity,

250
00:17:19,787 --> 00:17:22,049
but we kept flexibility in building them too.

251
00:17:22,510 --> 00:17:28,572
So we had a very instance-driven art approach with the art team and the design team where

252
00:17:28,572 --> 00:17:34,094
there was a lot of repetition, a lot of clicking together Lego pieces to really build an organic

253
00:17:34,094 --> 00:17:34,734
world.

254
00:17:34,734 --> 00:17:39,776
And that was a complete 180 on how we built things before at Crystal, and still do have

255
00:17:39,776 --> 00:17:41,296
a very crafted look.

256
00:17:41,677 --> 00:17:45,318
But ultimately we wanted that crafted look, but we wanted flexibility with it.

257
00:17:45,318 --> 00:17:49,619
So it was really about embracing this modular development process and pipeline as well.

258
00:17:49,619 --> 00:17:53,921
And that allowed us to ultimately get to the point where we could bring our partners to

259
00:17:53,921 --> 00:17:54,941
work with us.

260
00:17:54,941 --> 00:17:59,582
And we had a robust outsourcing pipeline that by the end of production we were able to actually

261
00:17:59,582 --> 00:18:04,404
send out a rough version of a level in Graybox that had been designed with modules.

262
00:18:04,984 --> 00:18:11,112
over to partners overseas in Shanghai and we would get back an alpha quality level at the end.

263
00:18:11,112 --> 00:18:16,699
It required some touch-up and finishing but ultimately was produced with external partners

264
00:18:16,699 --> 00:18:20,804
which was an amazing feat when we have a very high bar for our game.

265
00:18:22,347 --> 00:18:26,908
We had multiple cinematic production companies through production as well, so we worked externally

266
00:18:26,908 --> 00:18:30,829
with a number of partners on over 90 minutes of story content for cinematics.

267
00:18:30,829 --> 00:18:34,250
So it was a very big production overall.

268
00:18:34,250 --> 00:18:38,852
I think one of the key things that we did in the last couple of games, including this

269
00:18:38,852 --> 00:18:42,593
one, is this philosophy is know as you go, as I put it.

270
00:18:42,593 --> 00:18:48,115
And essentially we put quality as the premium, which makes it very difficult to schedule.

271
00:18:48,115 --> 00:18:49,495
So ultimately we put...

272
00:18:50,115 --> 00:18:57,585
The emphasis on knowing every step of the way whether we were actually achieving what we wanted to achieve from a quality perspective.

273
00:18:57,585 --> 00:19:08,538
And this allowed us to scope along the way when we were off in time or off in targets and shape and change our production in order to maintain quality and deliver against our high goals.

274
00:19:09,700 --> 00:19:14,627
Ultimately, one of the problems we've seen in the past is if you deliver things at 50%

275
00:19:14,627 --> 00:19:18,813
or 60% at alpha and don't take it all the way up, it can be difficult to schedule that

276
00:19:18,813 --> 00:19:20,816
post-production part of the project.

277
00:19:20,816 --> 00:19:24,482
Quite often we see, and I've seen, projects really get to the point...

278
00:19:24,502 --> 00:19:27,484
where they've actually taken too much time in production,

279
00:19:27,484 --> 00:19:32,128
they haven't really understood how long it takes to get to the quality bar they're aiming for,

280
00:19:32,128 --> 00:19:36,873
and ultimately there's a block of time, which is your alpha to bug fixing to shipping,

281
00:19:36,873 --> 00:19:41,156
and that is relatively immovable at that point, because it's very late in the production process.

282
00:19:41,597 --> 00:19:49,041
So what we wanted to do on this was essentially not wait to find out exactly what game we were making, but be sure every step of the way.

283
00:19:49,041 --> 00:19:51,522
So it had to be great at every milestone.

284
00:19:51,522 --> 00:19:55,584
And that was really our philosophy on the last few games at Crystal, that ultimately...

285
00:19:56,765 --> 00:20:01,268
If you're not great every step of the way, then don't expect to be great at the end.

286
00:20:01,268 --> 00:20:06,071
So we wanted every milestone to be great and we wanted to know whether we were on or off.

287
00:20:06,071 --> 00:20:10,514
And ultimately, even though we use production schedules to drive our metrics

288
00:20:10,514 --> 00:20:15,558
and we use production to really calibrate what we're doing and how fast we're going,

289
00:20:15,558 --> 00:20:15,958
the sticks...

290
00:20:16,418 --> 00:20:19,622
and the screen really are our ultimate production schedule.

291
00:20:19,622 --> 00:20:22,986
And it's about picking up the controller, playing the game, and saying,

292
00:20:22,986 --> 00:20:27,511
is it great? And if not, scope accordingly, change, fix it,

293
00:20:27,511 --> 00:20:29,713
and do whatever we can to get that right.

294
00:20:29,713 --> 00:20:33,778
So we were iterating to make sure that we held up that bar every step of the way.

295
00:20:34,479 --> 00:20:39,641
It's important you don't drink your own Kool-Aid and you're not the one saying it's great, but other people are too.

296
00:20:39,641 --> 00:20:42,463
Ultimately, we're making this for an audience.

297
00:20:42,463 --> 00:20:50,487
So it was important that we also brought that audience into Crystal and we got validation along the way that what we thought was great was actually working for them too.

298
00:20:50,487 --> 00:20:53,109
So we have a focus testing lab at Crystal.

299
00:20:53,689 --> 00:20:59,114
We had focus testing from pre-production all the way through to the end of the production,

300
00:20:59,114 --> 00:21:03,379
roughly every two weeks early on in pre-production, through production,

301
00:21:03,379 --> 00:21:08,664
going down to every week and almost every day as we got through to the end of the project.

302
00:21:08,664 --> 00:21:13,108
And that was key in terms of understanding whether our choices from a design standpoint

303
00:21:13,108 --> 00:21:16,411
were actually working when people got their hands on the sticks.

304
00:21:19,045 --> 00:21:24,186
I think one of the other biggest things we did was build our game as episodic chunks.

305
00:21:24,186 --> 00:21:27,147
And this was a very different way of building.

306
00:21:27,147 --> 00:21:34,070
We had built our game in contiguous chunks of content that were almost products in themselves

307
00:21:34,070 --> 00:21:36,330
within a larger production cycle.

308
00:21:36,330 --> 00:21:40,212
So they were developed to an alpha quality before we moved on.

309
00:21:40,212 --> 00:21:44,273
And ultimately, if we didn't hit what we felt from a quality standpoint within these chunks,

310
00:21:44,273 --> 00:21:46,574
they were roughly about three hours each.

311
00:21:47,094 --> 00:21:54,241
Then we would iterate until we did and we would scope the remainder of the project to make sure that we still hit our timelines that we needed to.

312
00:21:54,241 --> 00:22:01,888
And this allowed, if we were productizing along the way and essentially making nuggets of product that were three hour chunks,

313
00:22:01,888 --> 00:22:07,153
what we could do is really very clearly see where we were on or we were off and make...

314
00:22:08,317 --> 00:22:13,318
choices along the way. And as we said, it's game development, so it's never perfect and

315
00:22:13,318 --> 00:22:17,139
you're always making choices. So the more knowledge you have and the more data you have

316
00:22:17,139 --> 00:22:21,941
about whether you're on or off from a quality standpoint, if you're putting that as a premium,

317
00:22:21,941 --> 00:22:24,161
it allows for better choices down the line.

318
00:22:25,242 --> 00:22:29,985
So we made many scoping decisions along the way around the content at the end of each one of these chunks,

319
00:22:29,985 --> 00:22:32,147
which we're actually going to show shortly some videos of.

320
00:22:32,147 --> 00:22:36,070
We could review it, we could refine at the end of every episode,

321
00:22:36,070 --> 00:22:41,114
and we could come back to the next episodic chunk that the whole team was on at any one point

322
00:22:41,114 --> 00:22:42,695
and say, how do we do it better next time?

323
00:22:42,695 --> 00:22:47,318
And through that process, it really did get faster and quicker to produce the game.

324
00:22:51,675 --> 00:22:55,796
So moving into pre-production, again, that sense of it being a product really existed

325
00:22:55,796 --> 00:22:57,276
in our first playable.

326
00:22:57,276 --> 00:23:01,997
And ultimately, even though we spent quite a long time looking at different flavors of

327
00:23:01,997 --> 00:23:06,658
the game, and before hanging our hooks on survival, ultimately when we came to doing

328
00:23:06,658 --> 00:23:11,479
our first playable demo, we wanted to make that feel like a product in itself.

329
00:23:11,479 --> 00:23:14,380
And ultimately that had a beginning, middle, and end.

330
00:23:14,380 --> 00:23:18,741
It was a 30-minute experience, and we wanted it to feel like you could put it in somebody's

331
00:23:18,741 --> 00:23:21,542
hands, and it was as close to a shipping game as we could make.

332
00:23:22,322 --> 00:23:29,828
So we started that in 2010. It took about five months to develop our first playable demo.

333
00:23:29,828 --> 00:23:38,874
And I think a testament to that is, out of that first playable, it was taken to, as I said, a 30-minute chunk of shippable game almost.

334
00:23:38,874 --> 00:23:42,036
We actually presented that to Game Informer and they were...

335
00:23:42,317 --> 00:23:45,840
We were lucky enough that they put it on the front cover and really embraced what we were

336
00:23:45,840 --> 00:23:49,684
doing because they could see very clearly at that stage what we were making.

337
00:23:49,684 --> 00:23:53,427
So it was definitely one of those things internally, it was a great calibration tool for us to

338
00:23:53,427 --> 00:23:53,767
work with.

